00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:04.600
How do we manage the idea that
people just, doesn't everyone

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:06.620
tries to create
Uber for the next x,

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:08.170
or whatever it might be?

00:38:08.170 --> 00:38:11.700
How do we constrain it a bit?

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:18.180
I think the answer is
for any design to happen,

00:38:18.180 --> 00:38:19.980
you need constraints.

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:21.870
You have to set some
sort of constraint

00:38:21.870 --> 00:38:25.240
around a problem
space or a boundary.

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:27.590
Now, because we're
working typically

00:38:27.590 --> 00:38:32.550
at the executive level, they're
thinking of moonshot equivalent

00:38:32.550 --> 00:38:33.260
ideas.

00:38:33.260 --> 00:38:35.760
That's what you're trying
to encourage them to do.

00:38:35.760 --> 00:38:38.380
But the way I
constrain them is we

00:38:38.380 --> 00:38:41.090
use a technique called
Transformational Targets.

00:38:41.090 --> 00:38:44.190
It's a small, little
workshop that I

00:38:44.190 --> 00:38:48.380
run where we put basically
a radar on the wall.

00:38:48.380 --> 00:38:50.610
And we say to
them, what would be

00:38:50.610 --> 00:38:53.350
transformative
for your business?

00:38:53.350 --> 00:38:57.220
Describe something that would
radically change the way

00:38:57.220 --> 00:38:58.920
your business operates.

00:38:58.920 --> 00:39:00.754
Now, just to give an
example, for instance,

00:39:00.754 --> 00:39:02.670
in the cargo business,
and this is great stuff

00:39:02.670 --> 00:39:04.086
that I've been
learning since I've

00:39:04.086 --> 00:39:06.360
been working with
these companies,

00:39:06.360 --> 00:39:08.540
there's paper everywhere.

00:39:08.540 --> 00:39:11.610
Paper for paper for
paper for paper.

00:39:11.610 --> 00:39:13.614
It's unbelievable.

00:39:13.614 --> 00:39:15.280
The next time you're
getting on a plane,

00:39:15.280 --> 00:39:18.770
you see these cargo bays
going in underneath the plane,

00:39:18.770 --> 00:39:21.490
everything on that has
to have a piece of paper

00:39:21.490 --> 00:39:25.430
to describe what it is, what
it's about, who's it going to.

00:39:25.430 --> 00:39:27.950
It's all handwritten.

00:39:27.950 --> 00:39:28.592
It's passed.

00:39:28.592 --> 00:39:31.050
When you get on the plane, the
last thing to get on a plane

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:35.000
is a huge satchel of paper which
describes all the things that

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:37.550
are on the plane.

00:39:37.550 --> 00:39:41.180
They have massive issues
like double-typing,

00:39:41.180 --> 00:39:42.610
or can't read handwriting.

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:47.470
This is why all your bags
disappear most of the time.

00:39:47.470 --> 00:39:49.840
In that industry, when we
did the exercise with them,

00:39:49.840 --> 00:39:51.830
we were like, what
would be transformative

00:39:51.830 --> 00:39:53.100
for your business?

00:39:53.100 --> 00:39:55.720
And they were like, no paper.

00:39:55.720 --> 00:39:58.000
0% paper.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:39:59.401
So we were like, brilliant.

00:39:59.401 --> 00:39:59.900
OK.

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:03.320
That sort of gives
us a constraint.

00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:06.080
And they came up with other
things like financial measures,

00:40:06.080 --> 00:40:08.900
or people development,
and so quite a big radar,

00:40:08.900 --> 00:40:10.820
prioritized them,
and then coming up

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:12.240
with a shortlist of maybe four.

00:40:12.240 --> 00:40:14.320
I'd like to say
between three and five

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:15.770
that are
transformational targets.

00:40:15.770 --> 00:40:17.560
They have to be smart goals.

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:20.610
So they have to
say like 0% paper.

00:40:20.610 --> 00:40:25.960
Or plus 20% NPS
score in two years.

00:40:25.960 --> 00:40:28.600
They have to be
measurable and scientific.

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:31.020
And then, what we
do is when we start

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:35.470
to generate all these ideas, the
way we challenge them and say,

00:40:35.470 --> 00:40:39.670
will Uber for airlines
get rid of paper?

00:40:39.670 --> 00:40:44.520
And it's that sort of question
to challenge and constrain

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:45.930
it a little bit.

00:40:45.930 --> 00:40:49.275
And then, it gives us
something to test against.

00:40:49.275 --> 00:40:51.400
Again, we're creating this
governance framework all

00:40:51.400 --> 00:40:55.690
the time of well, in order for
an idea to be worth challenging

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:57.960
and moving forward,
it has to fit

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:01.110
within these transformational
targets we've set ourselves.

00:41:01.110 --> 00:41:03.810
And that again, gives us
another feedback mechanism

00:41:03.810 --> 00:41:06.460
to say, well, how can we make
this idea more transformative?

00:41:06.460 --> 00:41:07.800
And so on.

00:41:07.800 --> 00:41:09.370
That's the technique we use.

00:41:09.370 --> 00:41:14.560
But yes, definitely, when you're
in the Design Sprint world,

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:17.860
there's probably more of an
optimization of an existing

00:41:17.860 --> 00:41:19.620
problem.

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.500
But we get to that stage too.

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:22.870
You get there through iteration.

00:41:22.870 --> 00:41:26.330
So over time, the
challenge becomes clearer.

00:41:26.330 --> 00:41:29.060
But at the inception
of the workshops,

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:30.930
they're still quite
very broad ideas.

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:34.060
There's lots of fuzziness
around the outside.

00:41:34.060 --> 00:41:37.340
But we reduce that through
the testing cycles.

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:39.470
And the way we test
is generally they

00:41:39.470 --> 00:41:41.990
have to do two customer
interviews a week.

00:41:41.990 --> 00:41:44.270
So the execs have to sit
down with their ideas

00:41:44.270 --> 00:41:47.190
and showcase them to customers
feedback twice a week.

00:41:47.190 --> 00:41:50.100
We generally invite
in someone from a VC

00:41:50.100 --> 00:41:52.180
or a business
thought leader where

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:56.620
they have to pitch to
someone external in the room.

00:41:56.620 --> 00:41:58.830
So they keep challenging
their own thinking about how

00:41:58.830 --> 00:42:00.530
the business stands up.

00:42:00.530 --> 00:42:03.210
And then, at the end
of every two weeks,

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:06.660
they've got to pitch back to the
CEO of the entire organization

00:42:06.660 --> 00:42:09.270
and say, this is
what we've learned.

00:42:09.270 --> 00:42:11.270
This is what we're
going to do next.

00:42:11.270 --> 00:42:13.550
Do you want to keep
investing in this?

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:17.900
So we even apply experimentation
to the process itself.

00:42:17.900 --> 00:42:20.780
Because if they invest in two
or three weeks' worth of work,

00:42:20.780 --> 00:42:22.830
and they're like, this
isn't working for us.

00:42:22.830 --> 00:42:23.330
Cool.

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:25.200
Let's kill it.

00:42:25.200 --> 00:42:27.090
We've just been lucky
enough, I don't know,

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:29.310
maybe, I'd like to think
that we're actually

00:42:29.310 --> 00:42:30.760
working in a good way.

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:33.280
But everyone who's got to
that stage has kept investing,

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:34.404
wants to keep going.

00:42:34.404 --> 00:42:35.820
But again, it's a
different person

00:42:35.820 --> 00:42:37.470
to challenge your thinking.

00:42:37.470 --> 00:42:39.430
You've always got to
keep bringing people in

00:42:39.430 --> 00:42:42.040
to challenge the
bias in the room.

00:42:42.040 --> 00:42:44.970
Eventually, we'll all think
something's a great idea.

00:42:44.970 --> 00:42:48.500
So we show it to a customer to
get a different perspective.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:51.210
Eventually we'll, again, think
everything's a great idea.

00:42:51.210 --> 00:42:52.870
We'll show it to
someone who's a VC,

00:42:52.870 --> 00:42:55.814
give us a different
type of feedback.

00:42:55.814 --> 00:42:57.480
That's what we try
to propagate and live

00:42:57.480 --> 00:43:00.320
